Then, attempts were made to weave them into fabric.
   In 1893 a glass fabric, which sold for $25.00 a yard
 when the best silks were only $1.25, was tailored into a
 dress and exhibited at the Chicago World Fair. But, it
 had more value to its designer, Edward Libbey, as a
 novelty than as a garment-the fibers were too coarse
 and inflexible to allow the wearer to sit down, and it
 could not be creased or folded.
   Years of experimentation were culminated in the 1930's
 as many industries explored the possibilities of producing
 glass fiber. However, nearly three years of laboratory re-
 search were necessary to perfect a method of making
 filaments of molten glass into resilient fibers. Another
 four years passed before glass fibers could be assured a
 future, promising enough to commence commercial pro-
 duction. Now, in the present jet age, industry is con-
 stantly searching for fabricating materials which are
 lighter, but stronger-adaptable, yet inexpensive. No one
 material has more completely suited the demand than
 fiber glass.

 UNIQUE COMBINATION OF PROPERTIES
 Fiber glass has a unique combination of physical and
 chemical properties which is making it one of today's
 basic fabricating and structural materials. Used as a
 reinforcement in conjunction with the new resins, includ-
 ing the polyesters, phenolics, epoxys, furanes, silicones or
 the thermoplastics, it can be molded into forms or made
 into laminates possessing tremendous impact strength.
 Pound for pound, these combinations have a higher
 strength-to-weight ration than any of the commonly used
 fabricating materials, including steel. Fiber glass fila-
ments can be produced with a tensile strength exceeding


SKYSCRAPER ENGINEER



200,000 p.s.i. This is considerably greater than 30,000 to
50,000 p.s.i. for rayon and 65,000 to 85,000 p.s.i. for nylon.
The strength of fiber glass yarns is unaffected by tempera-
tures up to 400' F. If subjected to higher temperatures,
there is a progressive decrease in strength, but, even at
temperatures at 700* F., more than half of the original
strength is maintained. Excellent dimensional stability
is verified by the fact that individual fibers, at maximum
stress, register only a 3% elongation. Fiber glass is not
influenced by atmospheric changes and will not shrink
or stretch any more than the glass in our windows. It is
chemically stable, has no color, and cannot burn, rust,
mildew, rot, or produce any odor. Fiberglass cannot oxi-
dize, since all of the constituent elements of glass. are
already completely oxidized in the production process.
With the exception of hot phosphoric and hydrofluoric,
it is impermeable to acids and weak alkalies. Since it is
a true glass, fiber glass is non-cellular and therefore com-
pletely wetproof beyond surface wetting. These proper-
ties combine to make fiber glass virtually ageless.
PRODUCTION OF GLASS YARN AND MAT
  The production of this wondrous fiber begins with the
accurate weighing and combining of the eight basic raw
materials . . . silica, limestone, boric acid, clay, fluorspar,
sodium sulphate, ammonium sulphate, dolomite, and coal.
This is controlled automatically from a control panel in
the "batch control center." When the "batch," as the
mixture of raw materials is called, is gathered, the approx-
imately 3,200 pounds of raw materials is conveyed to the
batch delivery system. Here it is transferred to smaller
buckets which are moved to a receiving station and then
to the melting furnaces as needed. In the furnaces, the
raw materials are reduced to molten glass at temperatures
ranging from 2300' F. to 2800" F., depending on the
finished product.
  The molten glass is allowed to flow, by gravity, through
microscopic orifices in platinum bushings, mounted on
the furnace. The number of holes in the bushings ranges
from 200 to 1200, again depending on the type of fiber
being produced. As the streams of glass emerge, they are
sprayed with a chemical binder.
  If the batch is to be made into superfine fiber glass, the
streams of molten glass are then blasted with jets of steam,
which attenuates it into a filmy mass. The superfine glass
pieces fall to a conveyor belt and are removed to be dried
and pressed into blankets. These mats are the form of
fiber glass we know as insulation and sound deadening
material. Fiber glass mats may also be utilized in some
of the final molding processes.
  If yarn is to be drawn from the batch, the streams of
molten glass are gathered on high-speed winders at a rate
of over two miles per minute. Since the winder moves so
rapidly, the glass seeping through the orifices is submitted
to a tension and is drawn into minute filaments. Some
may be as thin as .0002 inches in diameter. This is about
1/300 the diameter of a human hair. This extreme thin-
ness is the property which gives fiber glass fabrics their
flexibility.
