ED UCA TION


By WILLIAM F. SINGLETON


The purpose of an engineering college is to educate.
This seems like an obvious statement, but the expanse
of the word "educate" is not so obvious. For an engineer-
ing college, the prime objective is to stimulate the student
to the joy of learning. This is done by presenting the
fundamental laws and methods of the students' chosen
profession and of the fields in the periphery of his own,
with the hope he will extend himself not only in the
learning of these basic laws but in further study either
on the graduate level or in industry. This job is carried
out by the faculty, and, in order for them to be able to
relate the fundamentals to possible application, they must
keep abreast of the new techniques that are constantly
being developed in this world of dynamic thinking. This
requires many hours of reading and study, and often times
it requires a deviation from the teaching profession while
these advanced ideas are studied and made feasible for
classroom presentation.
  Since the great majority of engineering students will
eventually find themselves in the industries of the world,
a part of the education process is to orient the student to
these industries. This, of course, is a difficult job with
the many diversified industries existent in our own coun-
try and throughout the world. This duty is carried out


  WILLIAM F. SINGLETON, a senior E.E. is the Cir-
cluation Manager for the SKYSCRAPER ENGINEER.
Bill is also a member of Phi Eta Sigma, Druids, Omicron
Delta Kappa, Eta Kappa Nit, I.R.E., and A.I.E.E. He is
the President of the Pennsylvania Society of Professional
Engineers (Student Chapter) and of the Engineering and
Mines Cabinet.


by the administrators through their efforts to present
numerous speakers who are aware of this necessity. In
addition, the student chapter of the Pennsylvania Society
of Professional Engineers offers outstanding programs
which attempt to point out the necessity of ethical con-
duct on the part of the engineer and his duties as a
citizen of the United States. The technical societies in
the various engineering fields, also offer seminar programs
consisting, for the most part, of people directly from in-
dustry who present particular subjects. At the conclusion
of the programs the student body is free to ask questions.
  Another aspect of the word "educate" which is on a
par with the gaining of technical skills and techniques,
is the necessity to communicate and work with other
people. In many cases the engineer will be working side
by side with non-technical people and in order to "get
the job done" he must be able to instruct and explain to
these people his needs and desires. Then, when he does
complete the project, he must sell it not only to his su-
periors, but often he must instruct the salesmen and
servicemen in its operation in order that the object might
be sold. In the case of the engineer employed by the very
small organization the necessity of communication is even
more acute because he often finds that he does the research,
design, development, production, and selling of a particu-
lar item which means he ultimately must deal with the
layman, the person who has no knowledge whatsoever
of the technical complexities involved. Then, of course,
there is the life of the consulting and teaching engineer
whose very sub-title bears out the definite need and ability
to present ideas.
  So, the obvious conclusion is that unless one wants to
be put into a corner of the office with heaps of raw data,
stacks of graph paper, a well greased slide rule, and all
the formulas necessary to grind out the answers, which in
turn will probably be presented to an engineer with less
technical skill but more "education," one had better
realize the necessity of communication.
  Now, the student who is completely oriented to the
block schedules will probably run to his advisor and ask
why Communication One was not put on his schedule
and he will politely be informed that no such course
exists. There are many courses available at the University
in Public Speaking, English, Literature, etc., which are of
tremendous importance. But the fact remains that for a
person to become adept at presenting his views and ideas
in a way that is understandable to all, he needs more than


SKYSCRAPER ENGINEER




this formal training. He needs practice in its application.
   In the School of Engineering and Mines this training is
readily available to any and all who seek it. Primarily,
this very important type of learning can be received
through the many activities and programs presented by
the Engineering and Mines Cabinet, which is the planning
body of the E&M Association.
   This group is comprised of an elected representative
from each class of every department in addition to repre-
sentatives from the Skyscraper Engineer and E &S M Bulle-
tin making a grand total of thirty-eight active members
plus a faculty advisor. An executive committee is elected
from this group consisting of a President, Vice-President,
Treasurer, Recording Secretary, Corresponding Secretary,
Coordinator of Committees, and Physical Plant Director.
These offices are presently held by: William Singleton,
Kurt Nestel, Richard Fusco, Charles Shawl, William Ma-
son, Nicola Marino, and Richard Hatala respectively. The
faculty advisor is Dr. Edward B. Stuart of the Chemical
Engineering Department.
   E & M Cabinet plans and promotes a diversity of activi-
ties so that not only the 38 active members gain the neces-
sary benefits mentioned earlier, but an equal opportunity
to work, play, and communicate with students of varying
desires, skills, and professions.

  One such promotion is the inter-departmental sports
program set up under the direction of Cabinet with Bill
Kelly as its chairman. The fact that Bill is not a mem-
ber of Cabinet points out that education of this sort
is available to those who seek it. The sports program
consists of all the major seasonal sports such as: touch
football, bowling, basketball, softball, etc. Any other
sport that is desired by the student body will be planned
and controlled by the sports committee upon request.
The construction of the new, olympic style swimming pool
at the University opens many doors for the future in this
area. In addition, there are more playing fields and ten-
nis courts in the planning stages which will make the
sports program more complete in the future.
  E Sc M Cabinet also conducts at least one social event
of major proportions during each trimester. This com-
mittee is headed by Larry Tavlirides who is working dili-
gently to increase interest in the social events and to
improve their quality but not their cost. In addition is
the Outstanding Senior Committee-chairman, Joe Balazs
-which polls the students and faculty and makes an
award to the outstanding senior of the School of Engineer-
ing and Mines. There also is the Outstanding Seminar
Committee with Gerald Murphy at the helm which judges
the various departmental seminars to see which one is
best furthering the orientation process. The Freshman
Interest Program attempts to enlighten the new freshman
to the many possibilities available to him with the hope
that he will more readily make the transition from high
school to college life.
  The Engineering and Mines International Travel and
Training Award, known as EMITT, provides an eight
week travel and training scholarship to Europe for out-
standing engineering juniors. The chairman of this com-


mittee is William Hosick, who received the award last
year and traveled to England. Of course the number of
these awards made is directly proportional to the funds
available, so Bill and his committee are working diligently
in an attempt to raise this money.
  In the field of publications, E g& M Cabinet originated
the Skyscraper Engineer which is now "on its own." In
addition, the E &c M Bulletin was started a few years ago
and it is presently run by editor-in-chief Ronald Schmid.
This is a weekly newsletter which attempts to present
topics of interest to all engineering students while main-
taining as high a level of personal interest as possible.
  Probably the major individual promotion of E & M
Cabinet is Engineers' Week. This is a presentation of
the achievements and accomplishments of the engineering
students to their parents, other students of the Univer-
sity, the general public and, in particular, to the high
school students of the area in the hope that it will aid
them in the choice of their profession. Engineers' Week
is truly an opportunity for each student to work with his
colleagues and since the Shamrock Award is made to the
department amassing the best overall score for the week's
activities, it is practically a necessity for each student to
help if the pride of his department is to be maintained.
The tremendous job of planning the festivities for this
week falls on the capable shoulders of Edward Kondis
and Richard Fusco. Of course in order to make an opera-
tion of this type a success, an outstanding job of publicity
is. necessary. This chore is being handled in yeoman
fashion by Ronakl Crawford.
  The diversified jobs within the E & M Association make
it possible for an engineer to receive more than a technical
education. The opportunities to initiate, develop, and
present your own ideas, to communicate, explain, sell and
work with fellow students are readily available to all
those who are willing to sacrifice some time and energy
to obtain a "complete educationg


