                                                          By RICHARD COVER, JR.


  Until the late nineteenth century, Newtonian mechanics,
or classical physics, prevailed over scientific thought and
theoretical research, for in Newton's time, mechanics was
the most successful tool for solving problems in the field
of physics. To explain the physical phenomena of nature
merely meant to present a mechanical interpretation, and
no one dreamed that this mechanistic mode of thinking
could be revolutionized.
  The latest development in physics at this stage of philo-
sophical conformity was the theory of the lumeniferous
ether, which was thought to be the transmitter of electro-
magnetic waves. Ether permeated all space and matter and
carried light waves in much the same manner air trans-
mits sound waves. Most important of all, it provided the
stationary standard of reference of absolute motion which
Newton's cosmology required.
  If a light beam, for example, was flashed from the back
of a rocket in outer space, its velocity would be equal to
the speed of light (in a vacuum) minus the speed of the
rocket. If the beam was flashed in the direction of travel
of the speeding rocket, its velocity would be equal to the
speed of light plus the speed of the rocket.
