   Ether, however, was still theoretical in its development
 and two American physicists, A. A. Michelson and E. W.
 Morley performed a historical experiment in 1881 to
 prove or disprove the existence of the ether. They set
 up a relatively simple apparatus called an interferometer
 (since it dealt with wave interference), which consisted
 of a system of mirrors arranged in such a fashion that a
 light beam could be split and flashed in different direc-
 tions simultaneously. According to the addition of ve-
 locities theorem, the speed of light of one ray should
 be faster than it actually is, and slower in the other
 (due to the earth's revolution). Such painstaking efforts
 were taken in executing the experiment that the results
 were not to be doubted. However, the utterly remarkable
 result was that Michelson and Morley were unable to ob-
 serve any alteration in the velocity of the light beams,
 regardless of their direction.
   If the speed of light did not change in the experiment,
 the apparent velocity of the earth through the ether must
 be zero! Scientists were faced with a serious dilemma:
 either the concept of ether, which had solved so many
 problems about electricity, magnetism and the electro-
 magnetic spectra had to be ignored, or the Copernican
 Theory that the earth is in motion had to be abandoned.
   Debate on the subject was split for a quarter century
 until a young Ph.D. in a Swiss patent office came forth
 with such a simple answer that it took the wits of a genius
 to see it. Dr. Einstein published his first article, "On the
 Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies" in 1905 and thus was
 born the Theory of Relativity.
 Einstein solved the ether enigma and the results of the
 Michelson-Morley experiment with two fundamental pos-
 tulates. The first answered the ether dilemma by stating,
 in effect, that all motion is relative. That is, there is no
 fixed standard of reference in the universe by which man
 can detect the absolute motion of a moving system. Mo-
 tion can only be defined as a change of position of one
body with respect to the position of another. "Every


SKYSCRAPER ENGINEER




motion in space (description of events) involves the use of
a rigid body to which such motion must be referred. There
is no such thing as an independently existing trajectory,
but only a trajectory relative to a system of co-ordinates
rigidly attached to some particular body of reference."
  Imagine that you are standing at the window of a uni-
formly travelling railway car, and drop a stone onto the
embankment.2 You then see the stone drop in a straight
line from your hand to the ground. An observer on the
embankment notices that the stone falls to the earth in a
parabolic curve, due to the inertial force imparted on it
by the moving train. Does the path followed by the stone,
in reality, lie in a straight line, or a parabolic curve. Re-
membering that all motion is relative, the stone travels a
straight line relative to a system of co-ordination rigidly
attached to the train, but relative to the embankment, it
describes a parabolic curve. It is incorrect, therefore, to
speak of absolute motion as such; motion can only be ob-
served if it is referred to some arbitrary system of refer-
ence.
  If the ether existed, it would be in a state of absolute
riotion, since it would be the only thing in the universe
which remained stationary. But it has now been proven
that only relative motion can be detected, therefore de-
tection of the ether is impossible. Newton pointed out
centuries ago that it is impossible to ascertain the move-
ment of a ship in calm waters by any experiment per-
formed inside the ship. Similarly, the motion of the earth
through the ether cannot be detected by any experiment
here on earth.
  The second fundamental postulate stated that the speed
of light is constant, relative to any observer. Considering
both basic ideas of Einstein, we may say in conclusion, that
all phenomena of nature are equivalent for systems mov-
ing relative to one another.
  Dr. Einstein discarded the ideal of absolute space when
he said that all motion is relative, and now the idea of
absolute time, distance and mass must also be thrown
away.
  The layman makes time an objective, almost tangible
quantity by referring his experience to clocks and calen-

