                             By JOSEPH SCUILLI

   Every year around St. Patrick's day, the University
 populace expects to see an army of green-derbied young
 men invade the lower campus from the "hill." While the
 rest of the University community is engaged in their
 normal activities, engineers are busy planning and pre-
 paring for "their week." Preparations are made to handle
 the busloads of high school students and alumni, which
 "Engineers' Week" always attracts. But why the green
 derbies? Why all the preparations? Why the busloads of
 visitors? In short, what is the purpose of this so-called
 "Engineers' Week?"
 Although some phases of Engineers' Week have been
 somewhat amended since their inception in 1956, it is
 still fundamentally based on its original purposes. The
 first and probably the most important purpose of Engi-
 neers' Week is to display the technical talents of Pitt En-
 gineering students. To accomplish this purpose, each de-
 partment designs and builds an original display depicting
 engineering principles as applied to a particular project.
 All the projects have several things in common. First,
 all displays are designed and built with the "theme" of
 Engineers' Week uppermost in mind. For example, the
 theme in 1961 was, "The Engineer's role in the growth of
 Pittsburgh." Many departments chose familiar Pittsburgh
 projects as their displays. This year the theme for the
 week is, "The Engineer's role in National Defense." Ob-
 viously, there are a multitude of interesting and informa-
 tive projects which can be built. Secondly, all projects
 must be designed so that technically untrained people may
 appreciate them. In this way they serve to educate not
 only the engineers who have developed them, but also the
 visitors who will inspect them. Finally, all departmental
 displays are open to the public, with special encourage-
 ment given to high school students, professional groups,
 and alumni.
 In addition to technical pursuits, Engineers' Week also
 possesses a very important social purpose. The social phase
of the week serves to build the spirit of the engineering
students to a high degree. There are a number of planned
events which are geared to this purpose. Early in the week
an informal "mixer dance" is held, which in the past has
not received a great deal of support. But as a preview to
this year's activities, count on attending the mixer dance-


