From the Dean


By Dr. G. R. Fitterer






    Time Out for MENTAL DIGESTION!


 This is the title of one of the most thought provoking
 little books* ever written. The author, Robert Rawls, de-
 scribes how a young army surgeon, Dr. William Beaumont,
 in 1822, patched up an Indian who had most of his ab-
 domen shot away in a hunting accident. The surgery was
 performed in such a manner that one could watch the
 process of food disgestion through a "window." Dr. Beau-
 mont experimented for several years with various types of
 foods, watched their assimilation and described his obser-
 vations in one of the most famous books in medical his-
 tory. He found that all foods needed some time for proper
 digestion. Some, of course, required more time than others
 for mastication, action with the stomach fluids followed
 by absorption into the bloodstream.
 Rawls goes on to illustrate that not all ideas can be
 digested mentally in a split second, as in speed reading,
 but many thoughts must be masticated for a long time
 through auxiliary reading, listening, discussing and argu-
 ing. They must then be "churned by the digestive juices
 of knowledge, experience, doubt, hope," etc. Meanwhile,
 the mind might reject the ideas, absorb a nourishing por-
 tion of it or assimilate it completely.
 These processes usually require considerable time. It is
 not often that the most profound thoughts are assimilated
 immediately upon contact. Also, as in the digestion of
 foods, not all people absorb the same ideas at the same
 * Updegraff Press, Scarsdale, N.Y.


rate. In fact an idea which gives nourishment to one per-
son might cause an allergic reaction in another because
of difference between individuals in the amounts and
types of background, knowledge, experience, etc., which
are needed for digestion.
  Every person who has engaged in research has some
time in his career encountered seemingly insurmountable
problems which are temporarily abandoned as hopeless.
Yet, after considerable digestion by the mind (more often
subconsciously), a relative simple answer to the problem
will suddenly be revealed to him. This often comes as a
surprise because at the moment of revelation, he is not
concerned about the original problem.
  Many of the engineering sciences are like this. Based as
they are on mathematics, physics, chemistry, etc., as well
as other engineering sciences, solutions to engineering
problems take time for mental digestion before all the
contributing factors can be pieced together as an inte-
grated whole. This has become the phase of engineering
education referred to as Engineering Design.
  All of this, of course, has a bearing on accelerated edu-
cational programs like the Trimester at Pitt. Some students
can absorb the material in an engineering curriculum at
a rapid pace and should be encouraged to take full ad-
vantage of such accelerated programs. Others, however,
need "time out for mental digestion" and should not accel-
erate their program faster than their own rate of as-
similation.
   One should not jump to the conclusion that the greatest
 benefit is always gained by those capable of the fastest
 rate of mental digestion. Some of the slowest eaters get
 the most enjoyment and benefit from their food.
   Recent surveys of the educational backgrounds of per-
 sons with a high degree of creativity indicates that a ma-
 jority of them were persons who require "time out for
 mental digestion"


